Albumin;ALB;Serum Albumin;Plasma Albumin.Definition: An albumin blood test checks your liver and kidney function. Albumin is protein in your blood plasma.

Alkaline Phosphatase;ALP;Alk Phos.Definition: An alkaline phosphatase (ALP) test measures the amount of ALP in your blood.

ALT (SGPT);Alanine Transaminase;Alanine.Definition: An ALT blood test is often included in a liver panel and comprehensive metabolic panel, and healthcare providers use it to help assess your liver health.

Ammonia;NH3;Plasma Ammonia;Blood Ammonia.Definition: Ammonia is highly toxic. Blood ammonia levels are usually less than 50 micromoles per liter (micromol /L), but this can vary depending on age.

Amylase;Amy;Alpha-amylase;Diastase;AMS;A.Definition: An amylase test measures the amount of amylase in blood or urine (pee). Amylase is an enzyme made by your pancreas and salivary glands that helps your body break down carbohydrates.

Apolipoprotein A1;Apo A-I;ApoA-I;Apolipo.Definition: A blood test that can tell you about your risk for cardiovascular (heart and blood vessel) disease

Apolipoprotein B;Apo B;Apolipoprotein B-.Definition: A blood test that can tell you about your risk for cardiovascular (heart and blood vessel) disease.

ASO;Antistreptolysin O titer;ASLO;ASO ti.Definition: Antistreptolysin O Titer is a blood test used to determine if you have an infection caused by a group A streptococcus bacteria.

AST;Aspartate aminotransferase;Serum glu.Definition: An AST blood test is often included in a liver panel and comprehensive metabolic panel, and healthcare providers most often use it to help assess your liver health.

Bicarbonate;Bicarbonate ion;Hydrogen car.Definition: A carbon dioxide (CO2) blood test helps healthcare providers determine if the body is balancing electrolytes properly.

UREA NITROGEN (BUN);BUN (Blood Urea Nitr.Definition: The blood urea nitrogen (BUN) test measures how much urea nitrogen is in your blood.

Calcium;Serum Calcium;Ca;Ca2+.Definition: Calcium blood tests check to make sure you have appropriate levels of calcium in your blood to be healthy.

Ceruloplasmin;Ferroxidase;Siderase;Coppe.Definition: Ceruloplasmin is a protein your liver makes. It binds to copper and carries it throughout your body. If you have low ceruloplasmin, it can point to a genetic condition called Wilson disease, a copper deficiency or other medical conditions.

Cholesterol, Total;Cholesterol;Lipids;Li.Definition: Your cholesterol numbers show how much cholesterol is circulating in your blood.

Creatinine;Blood Creatinine;Serum Creati.Definition: The creatinine clearance test checks your kidney function by looking at the amount of creatinine in your urine and blood. Creatinine is a waste product that’s typically filtered out of your blood by your kidneys.

Ferritin;Serum Ferritin;SF;Iron Storage.Definition: A ferritin test measures the amount of ferritin in your blood — a protein that stores iron inside your cells. This test helps healthcare providers determine if you have a healthy amount of iron in your body.

GGT;Gamma-Glutamyl Transferase;Gamma-Glu.Definition: Gamma-glutamyl transferase (GGT) is an enzyme that's mainly found in your liver. Healthcare providers use GGT blood tests to help diagnose liver conditions or to rule out certain medical conditions based on abnormal results from other liver enzyme tests.

Fasting Glucose;Glucose Fasting;Glucose;.Definition: A blood glucose test measures the level of glucose (sugar) in your blood. The test can involve a finger prick or a blood draw from your vein. Healthcare providers most commonly use blood glucose tests to screen for Type 2 diabetes, which is a common condition.

Hemoglobin;Hb;Hgb;Haemoglobin;Hemoglobin.Definition: A routine physical examination might include having a hemoglobin test to measure your hemoglobin levels. Hemoglobin is the main component of red blood cells. The test is most commonly used to detect anemia (lower than normal hemoglobin levels), which might make you feel fatigued, dizzy or weak.

HDL;HDL Cholesterol;High-density lipopro.Definition: HDL (high-density lipoprotein) cholesterol earned the title of “good cholesterol” because it helps you get rid of extra cholesterol. It brings it to your liver, and it ends up in your poop. A healthy amount of HDL cholesterol works against plaque buildup in arteries. This improves your risk of heart disease and stroke.

Iron, Total;Iron;Fe;Serum Iron;Ferrum.Definition: An iron test can show if you have too much or too little of this mineral in your system. It can check for conditions like anemia, or iron overload (excess iron).

PT.Definition: A prothrombin time (PT) test uses blood samples to measure how quickly your blood forms a clot. Healthcare providers often do this test to monitor your prothrombin levels if you’re taking the blood thinner warfarin.

LDH;Lactate dehydrogenase;Lactic acid de.Definition: An LDH (lactate dehydrogenase) test measures the level of LDH in your blood or other body fluid to check for tissue damage.

Lipase;Pancreatic lipase;Serum lipase;LP.Definition: Your healthcare provider may order a pancreas blood test if you have symptoms of pancreatitis or another pancreatic disorder. This blood test can determine if you have elevated levels of the digestive enzymes amylase and lipase in your bloodstream.

Magnesium;Serum Magnesium;Mg;Mg2+.Definition: A test called a serum magnesium test measures the amount of magnesium you have in your bloodstream.

MCH;Mean Corpuscular Hemoglobin;Mean Cel.Definition: Mean corpuscular hemoglobin (MCH). This test tells how much hemoglobin is in your typical red blood cell.

MCHC;Mean Corpuscular Hemoglobin Concent.Definition: Mean corpuscular hemoglobin concentration (MCHC). This measures the concentration of hemoglobin in a certain amount of blood.

Phosphor;Phosphorus;Blood phosphorus;Ser.Definition: Testing for low levels of phosphorus include a phosphorus blood test. You would provide a blood sample, and the test can determine how much phosphorus is in your blood. Abnormal levels could be caused by bone, kidney, or liver disease.

Platelet Count;Thrombocyte Count;PLT Cou.Definition: A platelet count is a quick, common test that counts the number of platelets in your blood. Platelets are cells that help your blood clot. A low platelet count might be a sign of certain cancers or infections. A high platelet count can put you at risk for harmful blood clots or stroke.

Potassium;Potassium Serum;Serum Potassiu.Definition: In the right amounts, the mineral potassium helps your nerves and muscles “talk” to each other, moves nutrients into and waste out of your cells, and helps your heart function.

Prealbumin;Pre-albumin;Transthyretin;TTR.Definition: An albumin blood test checks your liver and kidney function. Albumin is protein in your blood plasma. Low albumin levels might be the result of kidney disease, liver disease, inflammation or infections. High albumin levels are usually the result of dehydration or severe diarrhea.

Prolactin;Luteotropic hormone;Lactotropi.Definition: Prolactin is a hormone that’s responsible for lactation, certain breast tissue development and milk production. Higher-than-normal levels of prolactin in your blood can cause certain symptoms, such as irregular periods, infertility and erectile dysfunction.

Protein CSF;Cerebrospinal fluid protein;.Definition: A cerebrospinal fluid leak (CSF) is when you're leaking the fluid that surrounds your brain and spinal cord. CSF is vital to how your brain and spinal cord work, protecting and cushioning them from outside forces.

Protein, Total;Protein Total Serum;Total.Definition: The total serum protein test measures all the proteins in your blood. It can also check the amount of albumin you have compared to globulin, or what's called your A/G ratio.

RBC;Red Blood Cell;Erythrocyte;Red Blood.Definition: Red blood cells bring oxygen to the tissues in your body and release carbon dioxide to your lungs for you to exhale. Oxygen turns into energy, which is an essential function to keep your body healthy.

Sodium;Sodium Serum;Serum sodium;Na+;Sod.Definition: A sodium blood test (also called a serum sodium test) is a way for your health care provider to measure the amount of sodium in your blood. This test is often part of a group of tests that measure different substances in your blood.

Transferrin;Siderophilin;Beta-1 metal-bi.Definition: This test tells how much transferrin (a protein) is free to carry iron through your blood. If your TIBC level is high, it means more transferrin is free because you have low iron.

Triglycerides;Blood fats;Lipids;Serum tr.Definition: Triglycerides are a very common kind of fat in your body. They’re in butter and other fats in food. You also make triglycerides from extra calories to use later. But high triglyceride levels can raise your risk of issues like heart attacks and strokes.

Troponin;TnT;TnI;cTnT;cTnI;cardiac tropo.Definition: A troponin test looks for certain types of the protein troponin, in your bloodstream. Those types of troponin only occur in heart muscle cells and only enter your blood because of heart muscle damage. That makes troponin invaluable in diagnosing heart attacks and other heart-related problems.

TSH;Thyroid-Stimulating Hormone;Thyrotro.Definition: Thyroid-stimulating hormone (TSH) triggers your thyroid to release its hormones, which mainly impact your body’s metabolism. High TSH levels usually indicate hypothyroidism, and low TSH levels usually indicate hyperthyroidism.

Uric Acid;UA;Serum Uric Acid;Blood Urate.Definition: High levels of uric acid can cause gout and you'll need to try and lower it. If you have symptoms of gout, you need to test a uric acid blood test, which measures how much uric acid you have in your blood. You may also hear this test called a serum uric acid test, serum urate, or UA.

Globulin;Globulin, Total.Definition: Healthcare providers use globulin blood tests to measure protein levels in your blood. Your liver makes globulin, a protein. High levels may indicate autoimmune disease, infections or cancer. A low globulin reading may be a sign of liver or kidney disease. A globulin test may be part of liver function tests or a metabolic panel.

Albumin/Globulin Ratio;A/G Ratio.Definition: The total serum protein test measures all the proteins in your blood. It can also check the amount of albumin you have compared to globulin, or what’s called your A/G ratio.

Bilirubin Indirect;BILIRUBIN, INDIRECT.Definition: A bilirubin test measures bilirubin levels in your blood. Bilirubin is the yellow pigment in bile. You might have high bilirubin levels if your liver is having trouble processing bilirubin into bile, or if your bile ducts are blocked.

EGFR.Definition: Healthcare providers use estimated glomerular filtration rate (eGFR) to determine if you have kidney disease, and if so, what stage. eGFR measures your kidneys’ ability to filter toxins or waste from your blood.

Carbon Dioxide;Carbon Dioxide, Total.Definition: A carbon dioxide (CO2) blood test helps healthcare providers determine if the body is balancing electrolytes properly.

Iron Binding Capacity.Definition: A TIBC (total iron-binding capacity) test is one of a few tests healthcare providers use to diagnose iron-related conditions, like anemia and hemochromatosis. They often compare the results to iron and ferritin blood test results.

LDL-Cholesterol;LDL, Calculated.Definition: Your cholesterol numbers show how much cholesterol is circulating in your blood. Your LDL (“bad” cholesterol) should be below 100.

CHOL/HDLC Ratio;Chol/HDL Ratio.Definition: This is your total cholesterol divided by your HDL.

MCV.Definition: MCV (mean corpuscular volume) measures the average size of your red blood cells. It’s included in a common blood test called a complete blood count (CBC). Considered alongside the results of other tests, an MCV blood test can help your healthcare provider determine if you have anemia, liver disease or other conditions.

RDW.Definition: An RDW blood test measures your red blood cells’ variation in size and volume. It’s just one test that’s part of a more extensive blood workup called a complete blood count (CBC). An RDW blood test can help your healthcare provider diagnose anemia and other related conditions, along with other tests that provide information about your red blood cells.

MPV.Definition: An MPV blood test measures the average size of your platelets, the blood cells that help your blood clot. When considered alongside other test results on a complete blood count (CBC), an MPV test can help your healthcare provider diagnose blood disorders and other conditions.

Absolute Neutrophils.Definition: Neutrophils help your immune system fight infections and heal injuries. Neutrophils are the most common type of white blood cell in your body. An absolute neutrophil count identifies whether your body has enough neutrophils or if your count is above or below a healthy range.

Absolute Lymphocytes.Definition: The absolute lymphocytes count is part of a complete blood count (CBC). An absolute lymphocytes count tells you the number of cells as an absolute number instead of as a percentage.

Absolute Monocytes.Definition: An absolute monocyte count identifies how many monocytes are present in a sample of your blood. The results from this test identify whether or not your monocyte count is normal, too high or too low.

Absolute Eosinophils.Definition: A blood test, similar to the complete blood count, specifically identifies how many eosinophils are in a sample of your blood. After your healthcare provider removes a sample of your blood from your vein, they will examine that sample under a microscope. They will add dye to the sample to make your cells more visible, then count how many eosinophils are present in the sample out of 100 cells. That percentage is multiplied by your white blood cell count to give an absolute eosinophil count.

Absolute Basophils.Definition: An absolute basophil count identifies how many basophils are present in a sample of your blood.

WBC;White Blood Cell Count;Leukocyte Cou.Definition: White blood cells are a part of your immune system that protects your body from infection. These cells circulate through your bloodstream and tissues to respond to injury or illness by attacking any unknown organisms that enter your body.

Hematocrit;HCT.Definition: A hematocrit test is a simple blood test that measures the percentage of red blood cells in your blood. Red blood cells are important because they carry oxygen throughout your body. Test results showing low or high hematocrit levels may be signs of blood disorders or other medical conditions.
